1. Project Success Rate
Measure the percentage of projects completed on time, within budget, and meeting objectives. This is your north star metric.

2. Resource Utilization
Track how efficiently your team members are allocated across projects. Aim for 70-85% utilization for optimal productivity.

3. Budget Variance
Monitor the difference between planned and actual project costs. A variance within 10% is generally considered acceptable.

4. Schedule Variance
Measure how projects are tracking against timelines. Early identification of delays enables proactive intervention.

5. Stakeholder Satisfaction
Regular surveys help gauge how well the PMO is meeting stakeholder expectations and supporting business objectives.

6. Risk Management Effectiveness
Track the percentage of identified risks that are successfully mitigated before becoming issues.

7. Change Request Volume
Monitor the number and impact of change requests to identify scope creep patterns and improve initial planning.

8. Benefits Realization
Measure actual benefits achieved versus planned benefits to demonstrate ROI and strategic value.

9. Portfolio Health
Assess the overall health of your project portfolio using red/amber/green status indicators.

10. PMO Cost as Percentage of Portfolio
Calculate PMO operating costs relative to total portfolio value to demonstrate efficiency.

Implement these KPIs using a balanced scorecard approach, reviewing them monthly with leadership to drive continuous improvement.`
